# Avoid the word "cleavage" in prose

Don't use **"cleavage"** as a metaphor for a split, boundary, or division in any prose: docs, ADRs, specs, plans, READMEs, PR descriptions, commit messages, or code comments. The word is technically correct in the geological / structural sense but reads weirdly in technical writing because of its other common meaning, and the alternatives are clearer anyway.

Prefer the natural English alternative for the context:

| Instead of                           | Prefer                       |
|--------------------------------------|------------------------------|
| "the natural cleavage between X and Y" | "the natural split between X and Y" / "the natural distinction between X and Y" |
| "the cleavage is precise:"           | "the split is precise:" / "the boundary is precise:" |
| "the cleavage between Project 1 and Project 2" | "the boundary between Project 1 and Project 2" |
| "predicate / non-predicate cleavage" | "predicate / non-predicate split" |

Use whichever of "split", "boundary", "distinction", or "divide" reads most naturally in the surrounding sentence.
